---
import Canvas from "../layouts/Canvas.astro";
const styles = `
    .int-card {
      border: 1px solid var(--border);
      border-radius: var(--radius-md);
      padding: 18px 20px;
      background: var(--card);
    }
    .int-card .int-label {
      font-family: var(--font-mono);
      font-size: 10.5px;
      color: var(--text-muted);
      text-transform: uppercase;
      letter-spacing: 0.1em;
      margin-bottom: 6px;
    }
    .int-card .int-title { font-weight: 600; font-size: 14.5px; margin-bottom: 4px; }
    .int-card .int-desc { font-size: 12.5px; color: var(--text-muted); margin-bottom: 10px; }
    .int-card .int-meta {
      font-family: var(--font-mono);
      font-size: 11px;
      color: var(--text-faint);
    }
    .chip-row { display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 6px; }
    .chip {
      font-family: var(--font-mono);
      font-size: 11px;
      padding: 3px 8px;
      background: var(--muted);
      border: 1px solid var(--border-subtle);
      border-radius: 4px;
      color: var(--text-secondary);
    }
  `;
---

<Canvas title="15 · AI Framework Integrations — Sardis Canvas" currentId="integrations">
<Fragment slot="head">
  <style is:global set:html={styles}></style>
</Fragment>

<section class="hero">
        <span class="eyebrow">Canvas 15 · Product</span>
        <h1>AI Framework Integrations</h1>
        <p class="hero-lead">
          Sardis is the universal payment layer for every major agent framework. Not "works with
          a few" — every one that matters today ships a Sardis adapter in
          <code>packages/</code>, with the same policy engine, the same MPC wallets, and the same
          ledger underneath. The developer writes agent code; Sardis makes its money verifiable.
        </p>
        <div class="row row-wrap mt-24" style="gap:12px;">
          <span class="badge">19 published adapters</span>
          <span class="badge">70K+ SDK installs</span>
          <span class="badge">LangChain v1.0.0</span>
          <span class="badge">MCP-first</span>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section" style="padding-top:0; border-top:0;">
        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <span class="callout-title">Positioning</span>
          Frameworks come and go; money movement doesn't. By landing in every agent framework's
          native idiom, Sardis positions itself as the neutral payments substrate — the same way
          Stripe became neutral for web checkout. Developers don't choose "payments" any more than
          they choose "HTTPS"; they pick a framework and Sardis is already there.
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Why adapters exist -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Shape</div>
          <h2>Every adapter is the same three-line pattern.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            A framework adapter doesn't re-implement Sardis — it translates. Each package imports
            <code>sardis-sdk</code> (or <code>@sardis/sdk</code>), wraps Sardis primitives
            (<code>pay</code>, <code>check_balance</code>, <code>set_policy</code>,
            <code>list_transactions</code>, <code>check_policy</code>) as <em>native tools in that
            framework's tool protocol</em>, and exposes them as a <code>SardisToolkit</code>.
            The agent author writes code that looks native; the bytes on the wire are identical
            across every framework.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="diagram">
          <pre class="mermaid" is:raw>
flowchart LR
    LC["LangChain agent"]      --&gt; AL["sardis-langchain"]
    CA["CrewAI crew"]          --&gt; AC["sardis-crewai"]
    AG["AutoGPT block"]        --&gt; AA["sardis-autogpt"]
    OA["OpenAI Agents SDK"]    --&gt; AO["sardis-openai-agents"]
    CS["Claude Agent SDK"]     --&gt; AK["sardis-agent-sdk"]
    GD["Google ADK"]           --&gt; AD["sardis-adk"]
    BU["Browser Use agent"]    --&gt; AB["sardis-browser-use"]
    CK["Coinbase AgentKit"]    --&gt; AX["sardis-agentkit"]
    VE["Vercel AI SDK"]        --&gt; AV["@sardis/ai-sdk"]
    NG["n8n / Activepieces"]   --&gt; AN["node + piece"]
    MCP["MCP host (Claude/Cursor)"] --&gt; AM["@sardis/mcp-server"]

    AL --&gt; SDK["sardis-sdk (py) · @sardis/sdk (ts)"]
    AC --&gt; SDK
    AA --&gt; SDK
    AO --&gt; SDK
    AK --&gt; SDK
    AD --&gt; SDK
    AB --&gt; SDK
    AX --&gt; SDK
    AV --&gt; SDK
    AN --&gt; SDK
    AM --&gt; SDK

    SDK --&gt; API["api.sardis.sh"]
    API --&gt; O["PaymentOrchestrator → Pre-Execution Pipeline → MPC → chain"]
          </pre>
        </div>
        <p class="text-muted">
          Adding a new framework is a one-day job: wrap the five primitive tools in its tool schema,
          ship as a package, add an example. The policy engine, trust graph, and ledger don't change.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Group 1: orchestration -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Group 01 · General-purpose orchestration</div>
          <h2>Where most LLM agents actually live.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            Six frameworks. If someone ships an "agent" in 2026, it is almost certainly built on one
            of these. Each adapter returns a <code>SardisToolkit</code> whose <code>.get_tools()</code>
            plugs directly into that framework's agent loop.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="grid grid-2">

          <div class="int-card">
            <div class="int-label">LangChain</div>
            <div class="int-title">sardis-langchain · v1.0.0</div>
            <div class="int-desc">
              <code>SardisToolkit</code> → five <code>BaseTool</code>s (Pay, CheckBalance, SetPolicy,
              CheckPolicy, ListTransactions) plus a <code>SardisCallbackHandler</code> that logs every
              tool invocation to the Sardis ledger. Works with any LangChain agent (OpenAI Functions,
              ReAct, tool-calling).
            </div>
            <pre><code>pip install sardis-langchain</code></pre>
            <pre><code>from sardis_sdk import SardisClient
from sardis_langchain import SardisToolkit

client = SardisClient(api_key="sk_live_…")
tools  = SardisToolkit(client=client, wallet_id="wal_abc").get_tools()
# pass tools to any LangChain agent</code></pre>
            <div class="int-meta mt-8">Exports: SardisToolkit · SardisCallbackHandler · SardisPayTool · SardisCheckBalanceTool · SardisSetPolicyTool · SardisCheckPolicyTool · SardisListTransactionsTool</div>
          </div>

          <div class="int-card">
            <div class="int-label">CrewAI</div>
            <div class="int-title">sardis-crewai · v1.1.0</div>
            <div class="int-desc">
              Agent payment tools plus <em>pre-built Sardis agents</em> and task templates —
              "Finance Officer," "Spending Approver" — that drop into a CrewAI crew.
              Multi-agent crews share a wallet with per-agent policy overlays.
            </div>
            <pre><code>pip install sardis-crewai</code></pre>
          </div>

          <div class="int-card">
            <div class="int-label">AutoGPT</div>
            <div class="int-title">sardis-autogpt · v2.0.0</div>
            <div class="int-desc">
              AutoGPT blocks that expose Sardis <code>pay</code>, <code>check_balance</code>, and
              policy ops as first-class workflow nodes. 2.x bumped to match AutoGPT's block
              architecture refactor.
            </div>
            <pre><code>pip install sardis-autogpt</code></pre>
          </div>

          <div class="int-card">
            <div class="int-label">OpenAI Agents SDK</div>
            <div class="int-title">sardis-openai-agents · v1.1.0</div>
            <div class="int-desc">
              Sardis tools as <code>Tool</code> instances for OpenAI's Agents SDK — drop into
              <code>Runner</code> to give any GPT-class model policy-controlled payments.
              Complementary to <code>sardis-openai</code> (classic function-calling).
            </div>
            <pre><code>pip install sardis-openai-agents</code></pre>
          </div>

          <div class="int-card">
            <div class="int-label">Claude Agent SDK</div>
            <div class="int-title">sardis-agent-sdk · v1.1.0</div>
            <div class="int-desc">
              Tool definitions + <code>SardisToolHandler</code> for Anthropic's Agent SDK.
              Covers pay, hold, escrow, subscription, FX quote, policy, balance,
              transaction list, and mint — a wider surface than most adapters because Claude can
              handle richer tool schemas.
            </div>
            <pre><code>pip install sardis-agent-sdk</code></pre>
            <div class="int-meta mt-8">Exports: SardisToolkit, SardisToolHandler, SARDIS_PAY_TOOL, SARDIS_CHECK_BALANCE_TOOL, SARDIS_CREATE_HOLD_TOOL, SARDIS_CREATE_ESCROW_TOOL, SARDIS_CREATE_SUBSCRIPTION_TOOL, SARDIS_GET_FX_QUOTE_TOOL, SARDIS_SET_POLICY_TOOL, SARDIS_MINT_PAYMENT_TOOL, SARDIS_LIST_TRANSACTIONS_TOOL, SARDIS_CHECK_POLICY_TOOL</div>
          </div>

          <div class="int-card">
            <div class="int-label">Google ADK</div>
            <div class="int-title">sardis-adk · v1.0.0</div>
            <div class="int-desc">
              Wraps Sardis ops as <code>FunctionTool</code>s for Google's Agent Development Kit.
              Ships a <code>create_sardis_agent()</code> helper that returns a pre-configured ADK
              agent with wallet + policy wired up.
            </div>
            <pre><code>pip install sardis-adk</code></pre>
          </div>

        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Group 2: browser/automation -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Group 02 · Browser &amp; automation</div>
          <h2>Agents that click, type, and execute shell.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            Browser and code-execution agents have the biggest "oops I drained the wallet" risk —
            they touch live websites and run arbitrary code. Every adapter here force-routes spend
            through the policy engine before a browser action or shell command can spend money.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="grid grid-2">

          <div class="int-card">
            <div class="int-label">Browser Use</div>
            <div class="int-title">sardis-browser-use · v1.1.0</div>
            <div class="int-desc">
              Payment tools for the Browser Use agent. Converts an "agent shops on a real e-commerce
              site" flow from "trust the DOM" to "Sardis hold + checkout mandate" — actions are
              reversible until the agent explicitly captures.
            </div>
            <pre><code>pip install sardis-browser-use</code></pre>
          </div>

          <div class="int-card">
            <div class="int-label">Stagehand / Browserbase</div>
            <div class="int-title">sardis-stagehand</div>
            <div class="int-desc">
              Stagehand actions with a Sardis payment primitive attached. Agents running in
              Browserbase sessions get the same hold/capture/policy model as any other Sardis agent.
              TypeScript package.
            </div>
            <pre><code>npm i sardis-stagehand</code></pre>
          </div>

          <div class="int-card">
            <div class="int-label">Composio</div>
            <div class="int-title">sardis-composio · v1.0.0</div>
            <div class="int-desc">
              Sardis tools in Composio's tool marketplace — so any agent already pulling tools from
              Composio picks up Sardis without a code change beyond adding the tool name.
            </div>
            <pre><code>pip install sardis-composio</code></pre>
          </div>

          <div class="int-card">
            <div class="int-label">OpenClaw</div>
            <div class="int-title">sardis-openclaw · v1.0.0</div>
            <div class="int-desc">
              OpenClaw skill — makes Sardis payments a native capability for OpenClaw's
              computer-use agents. Same five-primitive pattern.
            </div>
            <pre><code>pip install sardis-openclaw</code></pre>
          </div>

          <div class="int-card">
            <div class="int-label">E2B</div>
            <div class="int-title">sardis-e2b</div>
            <div class="int-desc">
              E2B sandbox template that ships Sardis SDK pre-installed and pre-authenticated to the
              merchant's sandbox key. Agents that spin up E2B VMs to run code can immediately call
              <code>sardis.pay(...)</code> without a key-distribution dance.
            </div>
            <pre><code>e2b template init sardis-e2b</code></pre>
          </div>

        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Group 3: multi-agent / protocols -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Group 03 · Multi-agent protocols</div>
          <h2>When agents talk to each other.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            Agent-to-agent payments have a protocol problem before they have a payments problem.
            Sardis ships first-class support for the two multi-agent standards that matter:
            Google's A2A and Coinbase AgentKit.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="grid grid-2">

          <div class="int-card">
            <div class="int-label">Google A2A</div>
            <div class="int-title">sardis-a2a · v1.1.0</div>
            <div class="int-desc">
              Spec-compliant A2A server <em>and</em> client. Agent card discovery at
              <code>/.well-known/agent.json</code>, JSON-RPC 2.0 task lifecycle, SSE streaming,
              push notifications. Sardis extends with payment-domain skills (escrow, settlement,
              trust verification) delivered as <code>DataPart</code> payloads — standards-conformant,
              payments-aware.
            </div>
            <pre><code>pip install sardis-a2a</code></pre>
            <div class="int-meta mt-8">Exports: A2AClient, SardisAgentCard, A2APaymentRequest/Response, AgentDiscoveryService, SSE stream.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="int-card">
            <div class="int-label">Coinbase AgentKit</div>
            <div class="int-title">sardis-agentkit · v0.1.0</div>
            <div class="int-desc">
              Sardis payment actions for Coinbase AgentKit. AgentKit handles on-chain identity;
              Sardis handles policy and compliance on top — so a CDP-backed agent has
              non-custodial wallets and natural-language spend rules without rebuilding either.
            </div>
            <pre><code>pip install sardis-agentkit</code></pre>
          </div>

        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Group 4: platform -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Group 04 · Platform</div>
          <h2>Where agents run inside someone else's product.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            Not every agent is a standalone script. These adapters plug Sardis into platforms where
            non-engineers build agents: Vercel's AI SDK, n8n, Activepieces, ChatGPT custom GPTs.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="grid grid-2">

          <div class="int-card">
            <div class="int-label">Vercel AI SDK</div>
            <div class="int-title">@sardis/ai-sdk · v1.1.0</div>
            <div class="int-desc">
              Sardis tools packaged as Vercel AI SDK <code>tool()</code> definitions. Drop into
              <code>generateText</code>, <code>streamText</code>, or <code>ToolLoopAgent</code>.
              Ships ESM + CJS + browser bundles; type-safe via Zod.
            </div>
            <pre><code>npm i @sardis/ai-sdk</code></pre>
          </div>

          <div class="int-card">
            <div class="int-label">MCP Server</div>
            <div class="int-title">@sardis/mcp-server · v1.1.0</div>
            <div class="int-desc">
              50 Sardis tools over Model Context Protocol. Claude Desktop, Cursor, Windsurf, or any
              MCP host. Simulated mode lets a new user try Sardis from Claude Desktop without an
              account. See canvas 14 for the full tool list.
            </div>
            <pre><code>npx @sardis/mcp-server start</code></pre>
          </div>

          <div class="int-card">
            <div class="int-label">n8n</div>
            <div class="int-title">n8n-nodes-sardis · v1.0.0</div>
            <div class="int-desc">
              Community node + credential. Drop Sardis actions (pay, hold, approve, balance, policy
              check) into any n8n workflow. Credential type stores API keys in n8n's encrypted store.
            </div>
            <pre><code>npm i -g n8n-nodes-sardis</code></pre>
          </div>

          <div class="int-card">
            <div class="int-label">Activepieces</div>
            <div class="int-title">@sardis/activepieces · v1.0.0</div>
            <div class="int-desc">
              Sardis piece for Activepieces workflow platform. Policy-controlled payments as a
              drag-and-drop block for non-engineer builders.
            </div>
            <pre><code>npm i @sardis/activepieces</code></pre>
          </div>

          <div class="int-card">
            <div class="int-label">ChatGPT Custom GPT</div>
            <div class="int-title">sardis-gpt</div>
            <div class="int-desc">
              OpenAPI actions spec + GPT instructions. Gives a ChatGPT custom GPT the ability to
              pay, check balance, and enforce policies through Sardis — no backend code required
              beyond hosting the action endpoint (which Sardis provides).
            </div>
            <div class="int-meta mt-8">Artifacts: <code>openapi-actions.yaml</code>, <code>instructions.md</code>.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="int-card">
            <div class="int-label">OpenAI function-calling</div>
            <div class="int-title">sardis-openai · v1.0.0</div>
            <div class="int-desc">
              Classic OpenAI function-calling wrapper. Complements <code>sardis-openai-agents</code>
              for teams still on the bare Chat Completions API.
            </div>
            <pre><code>pip install sardis-openai</code></pre>
          </div>

        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Adapter anatomy -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Adapter Anatomy</div>
          <h2>Every adapter exposes the same five primitives.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            The surface area is deliberately tiny. If an agent can do these five things safely, every
            meaningful agent-payment use case falls out: order an API call, pay a vendor, refill a
            balance, split a cost between two agents, tighten a policy mid-run.
          </p>
        </div>
        <table class="data">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Primitive</th><th>Server op</th><th>Typical agent use</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><code>pay(to, amount, purpose)</code></td><td><code>POST /v1/payments</code> via <code>PaymentOrchestrator</code></td><td>Any outbound payment — API, vendor, user refund.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>check_balance(wallet_id)</code></td><td><code>GET /v1/wallets/&#123;id&#125;/balance</code></td><td>Decide whether to spend.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>set_policy(text | structured)</code></td><td><code>POST /v1/policies/parse + apply</code></td><td>Self-limit before a risky sub-task.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>check_policy(intent)</code></td><td><code>POST /v1/policies/check</code></td><td>Dry-run: would this pay succeed?</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>list_transactions(wallet_id)</code></td><td><code>GET /v1/transactions</code></td><td>Agent retrospection / reporting.</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <!-- Integration telemetry -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Observability</div>
          <h2>Where integration usage lands.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            Every tool invocation tags its payment with a framework hint (SDK-level
            <code>X-Sardis-Framework</code> header). The public repo preserves that transport contract;
            hosted analytics and dashboard visualizations live in the private product repo.
          </p>
        </div>
        <table class="data">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Surface</th><th>What it records</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><code>X-Sardis-Framework</code></td><td>Framework hint attached by SDKs and adapters.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>packages/reference-api</code></td><td>Normalizes framework metadata at the API boundary.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>packages/sardis-ledger</code></td><td>Persists framework context next to transaction/evidence records where applicable.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Private dashboard</td><td>Aggregates per-framework spend, transaction counts, and policy hits.</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <!-- Release -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Release</div>
          <h2>How integrations ship.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            Python integrations go via <code>.github/workflows/release-python-integrations.yml</code>
            (tag pattern <code>py-&lt;integration&gt;-v*</code>). JS integrations go via
            <code>release-npm.yml</code> (tags: <code>ai-sdk-v*</code>, <code>mcp-v*</code>, etc.).
            Each tag cuts a version-stable release; prerelease toggles go to TestPyPI / npm dist-tag.
          </p>
        </div>
        <table class="data">
          <thead><tr><th>Adapter</th><th>Registry</th><th>Release tag prefix</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>sardis-langchain</td><td>PyPI</td><td><code>py-langchain-v*</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td>sardis-crewai</td><td>PyPI</td><td><code>py-crewai-v*</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td>sardis-autogpt</td><td>PyPI</td><td><code>py-autogpt-v*</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td>sardis-openai / openai-agents</td><td>PyPI</td><td><code>py-openai-v*</code> / <code>py-openai-agents-v*</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td>sardis-agent-sdk</td><td>PyPI</td><td><code>py-agent-sdk-v*</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td>sardis-adk / a2a</td><td>PyPI</td><td><code>py-adk-v*</code> / <code>py-a2a-v*</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td>sardis-agentkit / browser-use</td><td>PyPI</td><td><code>py-agentkit-v*</code> / <code>py-browser-use-v*</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td>sardis-composio / openclaw</td><td>PyPI</td><td><code>py-composio-v*</code> / <code>py-openclaw-v*</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td>@sardis/ai-sdk</td><td>npm</td><td><code>ai-sdk-v*</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td>@sardis/mcp-server</td><td>npm</td><td><code>mcp-v*</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td>@sardis/activepieces</td><td>npm</td><td><code>activepieces-v*</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td>n8n-nodes-sardis</td><td>npm</td><td><code>n8n-v*</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td>sardis-stagehand</td><td>npm</td><td><code>stagehand-v*</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td>sardis-e2b</td><td>E2B template registry</td><td>—</td></tr>
            <tr><td>sardis-gpt</td><td>ChatGPT actions (hosted)</td><td>—</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <!-- Source of truth -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Source of Truth</div>
          <h2>Where to verify the claims on this page.</h2>
        </div>
        <table class="data">
          <thead><tr><th>Question</th><th>File</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Which integrations exist today?</td><td><code>ls packages/ | grep -E 'langchain|crewai|autogpt|openai|agent-sdk|adk|a2a|agentkit|browser-use|composio|openclaw|stagehand|ai-sdk|activepieces|mcp-server|gpt|e2b|n8n'</code></td></tr>
